<br>
So this can get quite tricky, and you have that two-sided coin for almost any instance in which a spawn-dispute may arise.<br>
<br>
Ok, lets discuss this topic as it was a very 'hot' issue in my other post.  Let me show ya..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   you must be within visual range of where the mob spawns.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well what about a random outdoor spawn, or a mob with placeholders in several locations?  Let me think of an easy example. Hrmm, the frenzied ghoul.  Most frenzy groups set up and hold &quot;camp&quot; in a room where they can not &quot;See&quot; the spawn when it pops. For most, civil, people, they see a group call &quot;Frenzy&quot; and they will respect that the spawn is camped.  Yet is someone really wanted to be an ass about it, they, technically, would not be breaking the rules to sit in the frenzy room itself can begin to camp it.  I actually remember this happening before Kunark came out, guk being so crowded at times that there were groups actually camping each individual spawn. Basically, the ___ + friends camping is the invention of the player-base.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  you must be loged in as the character that will use or engage the spawn.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yup, this one is true, though Ive seen tons of disputes about it. Part of it, in my opinion, is game design, I know when I was camping some pieces for my VP key, namely some ground spawns, I could not bear to sit and wait for something to just appear on the ground.  Ask Ketel sometime what a royal pain this is if you know him.  Sooo, I would park my cleric there, and play an alt character.  If someone were to pick up my &quot;spawn&quot; while I was gone, its my own fault. Not being there with the character that you are using before, and up to the point where your &quot;mob&quot; spawns, is only setting yourself up for frustration. Patience pays.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  you answer camp checks within a timely maner to your right to the spawn.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Im going to continue to play devils advocate here. There are so many exceptions to this rule and loopholes that I for one, couldnt consider it legit. If someone is sitting at a spawn and perhaps 1.) in battle spam 2.) briefly afk 3.) has the person asking on ignore...the list goes on, you get my point; a camp check isnt typically a reliable way to check a spawn. Going to the actual place where the mob or item spawns and seeing if anyone else is there will tell you.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   you get trained on and have to zone. in this case, you should, depending on the zone and mob, be giving propor ammount of time to get back to your original position.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So..what happened if someone repeatedly trains you. What defines &quot;proper&quot; time? What happens if it spawns while you are away? Do you have a right to be upset, or rather, just write it off as bad luck.<br>
<br>
The thing is, your rules work for &quot;most people&quot; but they are community rules. They are unwritten and unenforced.  All it takes is one person to break these so called &quot;rules&quot; and more will follow. They are plenty of people who will respect someone being visibly at a spawn, plenty of people that will respect a &quot;camp check&quot;, but the thing is, no one has to.<br>
<br>
Its kinda an innocent belief. Granted, it would be nice if we were all civil, polite, courteous, and respectful. You can deny that the people who arent like this exist, but you will only set yourself up for disappointment and stress. My personal theory, be on your toes, you never know when that one person who doesnt follow our &quot;common courtesy rules&quot; will stroll up. If they beat me to a spawn, no amount of whining, ranting, or tells is going to get it back. I guess at times like those, you can just be happy and proud that you would never do something like that, and take satisfaction that you uphold some sort of moral standard, even in this surreal world.<br>
<br>
Part of the &quot;Rush&quot; and fun of this game that we rarely acknowledege on a daily basis is that &quot;Race&quot; to a spawn, that bit of anxiousness when its about time for it to pop. Wondering if someone else may come along, wondering if your going to go LD and lose it, wondering if you might be afk when the thing you have been waiting for finally spawns.  Frustrating if you lose, joyful if you &quot;win&quot;. If we were constanly &quot;rewarded&quot; without any &quot;risk&quot; this game wouldnt be much fun.<br>
